  "prompt": "Which enzyme uses both NAD+ and NADP+ as a coenzyme?",
  "response": "The enzyme that uses both NAD+ and NADP+ as coenzymes is **isocitrate dehydrogenase**. This enzyme can catalyze the oxidative decarboxylation of isocitrate to \u03b1-ketoglutarate, and it is found in different forms in various organisms and tissues. The mitochondrial form typically uses NAD+, while the cytosolic and other forms can use NADP+. Depending on the specific isoform of isocitrate dehydrogenase, it can utilize one or both of these coenzymes in its catalytic process.",
